# Property Drawer System - Quick Start Guide

## 5-Minute Quick Start

### Step 1: Create Your Component

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using realvirtual;

public class MyComponent : MonoBehaviour, IRuntimeUI
{
    public bool enableFeature = true;
    public bool debugMode = false;

    void Start()
    {
        RuntimeUIManager.Instance.Register(this);
        RuntimeUIManager.Instance.RebuildUI(this);
    }

    void OnDestroy()
    {
        RuntimeUIManager.Instance.Unregister(this);
    }

    public void DrawCustomRuntimeUI(RuntimeUIBuilder builder)
    {
        var window = builder.AddContainer(RuntimeUIBuilder.ContentType.Window);
        builder.StepIn();

        builder.AddText("My Inspector");

        // Draw properties automatically
        RuntimePropertyDrawerRegistry.Instance.DrawProperty(builder, this, "enableFeature");
        RuntimePropertyDrawerRegistry.Instance.DrawProperty(builder, this, "debugMode");

        builder.StepOut();
    }
}
```

### Step 2: Add to Scene

1. Create an empty GameObject
2. Add your component to it
3. Ensure a `RuntimeUIBuilder` exists in the scene
4. Run the scene

### Step 3: See Your Runtime Inspector

The UI will automatically display:
- "Enable Feature" toggle button
- "Debug Mode" toggle button
- Interactive controls that update the properties

## Common Patterns

### Pattern 1: Simple Inspector
```csharp
public void DrawCustomRuntimeUI(RuntimeUIBuilder builder)
{
    builder.AddContainer(RuntimeUIBuilder.ContentType.Window);
    builder.StepIn();

    RuntimePropertyDrawerRegistry.Instance.DrawProperty(builder, this, "myProperty");

    builder.StepOut();
}
```

### Pattern 2: Custom Labels
```csharp
RuntimePropertyDrawerRegistry.Instance.DrawProperty(builder, this, "myBool", "Enable This Feature");
```

### Pattern 3: Multiple Properties
```csharp
// Draw multiple properties in a loop
string[] properties = { "prop1", "prop2", "prop3" };
foreach (var prop in properties)
{
    RuntimePropertyDrawerRegistry.Instance.DrawProperty(builder, this, prop);
}
```

### Pattern 4: Inspect Another Object
```csharp
public GameObject targetObject;

public void DrawCustomRuntimeUI(RuntimeUIBuilder builder)
{
    if (targetObject != null)
    {
        // Inspect properties of another object
        var component = targetObject.GetComponent<MyOtherComponent>();
        if (component != null)
        {
            RuntimePropertyDrawerRegistry.Instance.DrawProperty(builder, component, "someProperty");
        }
    }
}
```

